{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493185"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1247"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1247"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.04,0.17,0.14,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107970"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1247"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90383"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"101"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2664"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44897"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107970"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man is found during a regular check-up to have a late systolic ejection murmur at his right upper sternal border that radiates to the neck. He does not have any dizziness or chest pain, but has been experiencing some shortness of breath after exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn echocardiography he is found to have severe aortic stenosis with a left ventricle ejection fraction of 45%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic valve replacement","Statin therapy","Watchful waiting with serial echocardiography","Angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor (ACEI) therapy","Beta-blocker therapy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic valve replacement (AVR)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management in this patient because he has severe symptomatic aortic stenosis with reduced left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF). Once symptoms develop in severe AS, the prognosis worsens significantly, with a high risk of sudden cardiac death, heart failure, and rapid clinical deterioration if left untreated. Exertional dyspnea is an early symptom of left ventricular decompensation, indicating that the heart is struggling to overcome the fixed obstruction. Additionally, his LVEF of 45% suggests systolic dysfunction, which is a Class I indication for valve replacement according to current guidelines. AVR relieves the obstruction, improves cardiac output, and has been shown to significantly improve survival and quality of life in symptomatic patients. Depending on his surgical risk and comorbidities, he may be a candidate for either surgical aortic valve replacement (SAVR) or transcatheter aortic valve replacement (TAVR). Given the presence of symptoms, delaying intervention would be inappropriate, making AVR the best choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStatin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not the appropriate choice because while aortic stenosis is often associated with calcific degeneration, studies have not shown that statins slow the progression of the disease or improve clinical outcomes in patients with severe AS. The pathophysiology of calcific aortic valve disease is different from atherosclerosis, and despite initial hopes that lipid-lowering therapy could modify disease progression, randomized controlled trials have not demonstrated a benefit in reducing the need for valve replacement or improving survival. Therefore, statins are not the primary treatment for severe AS, particularly in symptomatic patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting with serial echocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate for patients with severe but asymptomatic aortic stenosis, as intervention is generally deferred until symptoms develop. However, this patient has exertional dyspnea, which is a symptom of hemodynamically significant AS. Symptomatic AS is associated with a poor prognosis, with a high risk of sudden cardiac death and progressive heart failure if left untreated. Given his symptoms, observation alone would be inappropriate, as it would delay definitive intervention and expose him to unnecessary risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not first-line in severe aortic stenosis due to the fixed obstruction to left ventricular outflow. While afterload reduction with ACE inhibitors is beneficial in many other cardiac conditions, in patients with severe AS, aggressive vasodilation can lead to hypotension, syncope, and reduced coronary perfusion due to the inability of the stenotic valve to adequately compensate for changes in systemic vascular resistance. Although ACE inhibitors can be cautiously used in some patients with heart failure and AS, they do not address the underlying mechanical obstruction and are not an alternative to valve replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-blocker therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is generally avoided or used with caution in severe aortic stenosis because these medications reduce heart rate and contractility, which can further compromise cardiac output in a patient with an already fixed stroke volume. Additionally, beta-blockers can blunt the compensatory increase in heart rate that is necessary to maintain cardiac output when stroke volume is restricted by the stenotic valve. While beta-blockers may be used in certain AS patients with concurrent conditions such as atrial fibrillation or coronary artery disease, they do not address the primary issue and are not an appropriate alternative to valve replacement in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETranscatheter aortic valve implantation (TAVI) is the desired method for valve replacement nowadays. This is because of the preference for less invasive treatment strategies and increase in patients\u0027 comorbidities that makes them less favourable for surgical aortic valve replacement (SAVR).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current indications for TAVI include patients with severe symptomatic AS and are of prohibitive or high surgical risk, some patients of intermediate surgical risk for SAVR and more recently a case-by-case basis for those with low surgical risk (PARTNER 3 trial). However, patient selection is strict and assessed by a heart team. The heart team involved in TAVI is a multidisciplinary team comprised of interventional cardiologists, cardiothoracic surgeons, nurse case manager, and many others. Patient suitability is assessed based on technical factors (valve morphology, access, etc.) and patient factors (comorbidities, frailty, etc.)\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with symptomatic severe aortic stenosis should be considered for valve replacement."],"references":["Kang D-H, Park S-J, Lee S-A, et al. Early Surgery or Conservative Care for Asymptomatic Aortic Stenosis. NEJM 2020 Jan 9;382(2):111-119.","Lindman BR, Dweck MR, Lancellotti P, et al. Management of asymptomatic severe aortic stenosis: evolving concepts in timing of valve replacement. JACC 2020 Feb 13;13(2):481-493.","Nelson AJ, Montarello NJ, Cosgrove CS, Roberts\u2010Thomson RL, Delacroix S, Chokka RG, Montarello JK, Worthley SG. Transcatheter aortic valve implantation: a new standard of care. Medical Journal of Australia. 2018 Aug;209(3):136-41.","Rahhab Z, El Faquir, N, Tchetche, D. et al. Expanding the indications for transcatheter aortic valve implantation. Nat Rev Cardiol. 2020;17:75\u201384. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41569-019-0254-6","Boskovski MT, Gleason TG. Current Therapeutic Options in Aortic Stenosis. Circulation Research 2021; 128:1398\u20131417."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90383"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1247"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90383"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T14:34:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T14:34:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1247"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107970"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":n